text: That's Don's takeaway
Was playing with a new guy in muldrotha yesterday, spent 20 minutes trying to convince him that locks weren't win conditions, don't think it ever got through.
I mean... Locks eventually lead to winning, if everyone wants to sit through you beaning them with your 2/3 commander.
depends on the lock even
I guess we're being pedantic by saying that some locks are win cons.

Basically what he was doing was playing and popping Plague Boiler every turn. He did eventually find a skeletal grimace to keep his muldrotha alive, but couldn't swing in with it because regenerate. I eventually shuffled his graveyard into his library, at which point he played a nevvy's disc out from his hand and continued to board wipe every other turn.
That was slow enough that the table killed him fairly quickly, but he made a 1 hour game into a 3 hour game, was basically the complaint.
Whereas if he'd been doing that with something more clever, or even just your standard Kokusho/Gary, he could've just won instead of prolonging misery.
Fair points.
Soft locks aren't a win con.
They can be a means to protect one. But if you don't establish a hardlock, you aren't winning with your lock.
or perhaps don't lock...
unless you want to pop 'n lock
You _know_ I want to pop 'n lock.
That kind of lock I can endorse...
The others...not so much.
For some people the misery IS the point

attachments.fallback: Someone sent a GIF in #hot-and-heavy using Tenor

text: Yes...I know they were bullied as a child and now they want to share their pain...

For as much as I like building decks that run locks, or figuring out new locks, I really don't like playing them due to the prevalence of the above situation where the game runs for 3 hours instead of 1.
I'd rather play 4 games in 3 hours.
Nah, I didn't get that vibe from this guy. Just a new convert from constructed play is more what it seemed like, who didn't entirely understand the distinction I was trying to make.
Which is probably at least as much my fault as his.
Same reason I don't like dedicated chaos decks.

"What's gonna happen?" 

"I don't know! But it's going to take us 3+ hours of dice rolling to find out!"

One of the main parts of commander is asking whether you're creating a play experience the pod is interested in (within reason). I think there's a lot of really, really, really, really selfish people out there who don't ask that and have no interest in asking it.
Their main concern is doing what they want to do, anyone else be damned.
Now, there's plenty of places a soft lock, chaos etc is a play expereince the pod is interested in.
That's a really good philosophical point, Dana.
So I'm not saying those things are a bad thing necessarily
I would read an essay with that as the main point.
Many subscribe to the 'there is only so much fun in a game of Magic, and I will have it all..." philosophy.
Or a tweet series.
I've been trying to figure out how to forumulate that. The problem is there's always going to be a flipside to, i.e. the people who will argue against any counterspell or removal
Hm.
It's why I added "within reason" but that's a sliding scale too
I think people who make that point miss the forest for the trees.
I don't think you need to consider it, just prepare for the comments, but clicks are clicks...
Now, if they're playing dedicated counterspells, they have a point, but complaining about stray counters as removal, not so much.
Counterspell.dec falls into the soft lock territory.
I think your main point stands on archetypes, rather than individual pieces.
I'll also admit I'm biased in that I want my ego stroked by winning with a weird commander or in an obscure way
On the counterspell.dec topic, how do you guys feel about [[Forbid]]?

heh
Forbid tends to have a cap at least, unlike Capsize that generally goes infinite, or Constant Mists that's almost always in a deck where they can recur the lands.
[[$forbid]]

I personally would put it in the same category as Capsize or Constant Mists, mostly just because the deck that plays it will have the means to draw cards as well, so if you can't unite a table around playing stuff into it, it's going to be pretty much the same result.
